The '''Tamil National Alliance'''  is a [[minority]] [[Sri Lankan Tamil]]  [[political party]] in [[Sri Lanka]]. It was formed as an amalgamation of moderate Tamil parties as well as number of former rebel groups. It has participated in election since 2001. Three of it's sitting members of the parliament [[K. Sivanesan]], [[Joseph Pararajasingham]] and [[Nadarajah Raviraj]] have been killed since 2006. The party supports negotiations with the rebel [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] to resolve the current [[Sri Lankan civil war|civil war]] in Sri Lanka. 

==Formation==
It was formed in 2001, just before the [[Sri Lankan legislative election, 2001|2001 elections]], and consists of the

*[[All Ceylon Tamil Congress]]
*[[Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front]] (A faction known as Suresh wing)
*[[Tamil Eelam Liberation Organization]]
*[[Tamil United Liberation Front]] (formerly the Federal Party)<ref name=TNA>{{cite web   | last =   | first =    | authorlink =   | title = TNA's 2004 Election Manifesto  |  publisher = [[Tamil National Alliance]]   | date =   | url = http://www.tamilalliance.net/index.php?page=policies&hl=en| accessdate = 2008-12-27 }}</ref> 

==Party manifesto and policies==
The party has come up with two party manifestos since 2001. In general the policies are based on the what is known as the [[Thimpu principles]] amongst Sri Lankan Tamil nationalists. They are 

# Recognition of the Tamils of [[Sri Lankan Tamil nationalism|Sri Lanka as a distinct nationality]].
# Recognition of an identified [[Tamil Eelam|Tamil homeland]] and guarantee of its territorial integrity.
# Based on the above, recognition of the inalienable right of [[self-determination]] of the Tamil nation.
# Recognition of the right to full citizenship and other fundamental democratic rights of all Tamils who look upon the island as their country.'

Further the party stands for 

# The immediate lifting of the economic embargo currently in force in parts of the northeast province
# The withdrawal of the residential and travel restrictions foisted on the Tamil nationality
# The immediate cessation of the war being currently waged in the northeast
# The immediate commencement of the process of negotiations with the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam ( LTTE) with international third party involvement.<ref name=TNA/>

===Relationship to the LTTE===
The alliance recognizes the LTTE as the sole Tamil national entity that has the right to negotiate on behalf of the Tamil people with the government of Sri Lanka. The alliance fully supports the [[Interim Self Governing Authority]] (ISGA) proposal made the LTTE. The alliance in general facilitates the eventual peace talks between the government of Sri Lanka and the LTTE directly over the Tamil national problem.<ref name=TNA/>

==Assassination of MPs==
{{See also|Human Rights in Sri Lanka|State terrorism in Sri Lanka}}
[[Image:Nadarajah Raviraj MP.jpeg|frame|right| Nadarajah Raviraj]] The first TNA Mmember of Parliament (MP) to be killed was [[Nadarajah Raviraj]]. A local human right organization, [[University Teachers for Human Rights]], claimed that they were near certain that [[Gotabhaya Rajapaksa]], current [[Permanent Secretary]] to the [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]] of the [[Government of Sri Lanka]], was involvement in the assassination. Further, it claimed that one Gajanayake, whose forces work under the [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]], was the main organiser behind the assassination.<ref name=TNA/> <ref name=UTHR2>{{cite news | title= Can the East be won through Human Culling? | date=2007-08-03 | publisher=[[UTHR]] | url =http://www.uthr.org/SpecialReports/spreport26.htm| work = | accessdate = 2007-08-26 }}</ref>The Sri Lankan government denied responsibility and strongly condemned his killing.<ref name=mod1>{{cite news | url = http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20061110_08 | title =Government strongly condemns killing of TNA MP| work =|publisher = Ministry of Defence|date = [[10 November]], [[2006]]}}</ref>

In the murder of [[Joseph Pararajasingham]] [[UTHR]] claimed the pro government [[TMVP]] and [[EPDP]] para military cadres were responsible for the murder. <ref name=Josep>{{cite news | first=Rajan | last=Hoole | coauthors= | title=Supplement to Special Report No.23: Before Time Obscures the Moul<U+2019>dring | date= | publisher=[[UTHR]]| url =http://www.uthr.org/SpecialReports/spreport23suppl.htm | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2007-12-06 | language = }}</ref><ref name=TNA/>

[[K. Sivanesan]] the third M.P. was killed on [[March 6]], [[2008]] by a roadside bomb near [[Killinochchi]] in [[LTTE]] controlled area in northern Sri Lanka while he was returning to his house in [[Mallaavi]]. The LTTE and other [[TNA]] MPs alleged that it was carried out by a [[Sri Lanka Army]] ''[[Long Range Reconnaissance Patrol (Sri Lanka)|Deep Penetration Unit]]''<ref name=TNA/><ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Pro-rebel_lawmaker_among_two_killed_in_Lanka_blast/articleshow/2843028.cms Pro-rebel lawmaker among two killed in Lanka blast]
</ref><ref>[http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=24875 Jaffna TNA MP Sivanesan killed in DPU Claymore attack ]</ref>, the Army has denied the allegation<ref name=sivanesan2>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7282205.stm Tamil MP is killed in Sri Lanka]</ref>.K. Sivanesan had alleged that he had been harassed by Sri Lankan Army earlier<ref>[http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2008/2/24993.html K. Sivanesan]</ref>.

Further [[Ariyanayagam Chandra Nehru]] a founder member of the [[NESHOR]] and also a former Member of Parliament of Tamil National Alliance elected from [[Amparai]] in Eastern Sri Lanka was ambushed and killed on February 7, 2005. The government had denied any responsibility<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/4245743.stm Killing raises Sri Lanka war fear]</ref>

==2001 Parliamentary General Election==
In the first general election contested by the TNA, the [[Sri Lankan parliamentary election, 2001|5 December 2001 election]], the TNA led by R. Sampanthan won 3.9% of the popular vote and 15 out of 225 seats in the [[Sri Lankan parliament]].

